Shift kernel-runtime
====================

This directory contains a Docker-based sandbox runtime used by Shift to
execute user-supplied Python code from `code_node` workflows in isolation
from the host and from other tenants.

Adapted from Flowfile project (https://github.com/Edwardvaneechoud/Flowfile),
MIT License (see LICENSE in this directory).

Differences from the upstream Flowfile kernel
---------------------------------------------
- The Flowfile kernel is a long-running FastAPI service with a persistent
  notebook-style namespace, artifact store, and disk-recovery layer. Shift
  uses *ephemeral* containers — one per code-node execution — with
  communication only via stdin (code) and a mounted /output volume (the
  result file). No FastAPI, no server, no persistent namespace. This
  trades the notebook UX for a much smaller attack surface.
- Polars-centric I/O is replaced with DuckDB-centric I/O: input arrives as
  a Parquet file at /input/table.parquet, output is written as
  /output/result.parquet.
- The shift-backend wraps each container launch with hard limits
  (CPU/memory cgroups, timeout, network=none, read-only rootfs) and
  forbids capabilities, privileged mode, and host mounts.
